00:00:00.263 --> 00:00:02.022
- [Instructor] So let's
review our knowledge

00:00:02.022 --> 00:00:05.022
of what it means to be an ideal gas.

00:00:06.854 --> 00:00:10.132
What key assumptions do we
make about an ideal gas?

00:00:10.132 --> 00:00:11.851
Well, the first assumption is

00:00:11.851 --> 00:00:14.518
no intermolecular interactions,

00:00:20.264 --> 00:00:22.496
and what do we mean by that?

00:00:22.496 --> 00:00:25.769
Well, an example of an
intermolecular interactions

00:00:25.769 --> 00:00:28.142
are something like, say, a hydrogen bond.

00:00:28.142 --> 00:00:32.192
Well, let's say that you
have two water molecules,

00:00:32.192 --> 00:00:35.423
two neighboring water
molecules, and that is...

00:00:35.423 --> 00:00:38.721
So you have an oxygen with two hydrogens.

00:00:38.721 --> 00:00:42.383
We know that the oxygen
end of a water molecule...

00:00:42.383 --> 00:00:43.901
And this is the gas form,

00:00:43.901 --> 00:00:45.817
so we're talking about water vapor here.

00:00:45.817 --> 00:00:47.085
So we know that the oxygen

00:00:47.085 --> 00:00:48.848
has a partially negative charge,

00:00:48.848 --> 00:00:52.448
and that the hydrogen end
has partially positive charge

00:00:52.448 --> 00:00:53.759
and these are attracted to each other.

00:00:53.759 --> 00:00:56.014
These are our famous hydrogen bonds.

00:00:56.014 --> 00:00:58.468
So that is an intermolecular interaction.

00:00:58.468 --> 00:01:00.842
We can think about dipole-dipole forces,

00:01:00.842 --> 00:01:03.457
which is similar because of
the polarity of the molecules.

00:01:03.457 --> 00:01:05.872
We can think about van der Waals forces.

00:01:05.872 --> 00:01:07.056
These various molecular interactions

00:01:07.056 --> 00:01:09.062
where just random chance one side gets

00:01:09.062 --> 00:01:11.392
a temporary polarity and might be

00:01:11.392 --> 00:01:13.277
attracted or repulsed from the other side

00:01:13.277 --> 00:01:15.322
of a neighboring molecule.

00:01:15.322 --> 00:01:17.124
For ideal gases, and for the

00:01:17.124 --> 00:01:19.091
application of the ideal gas law,

00:01:19.091 --> 00:01:22.121
we assume that there are no
intermolecular interactions

00:01:22.121 --> 00:01:24.536
or, if there are, that it's very....

00:01:24.536 --> 00:01:26.217
We assume an ideal gas has none of them.

00:01:26.217 --> 00:01:27.610
And, in real gases, in order to

00:01:27.610 --> 00:01:28.962
assume they're like an ideal gas,

00:01:28.962 --> 00:01:30.355
we assume this is very limited

00:01:30.355 --> 00:01:33.221
or that we can assume
they're not happening.

00:01:33.221 --> 00:01:35.596
The second key assumption is that

00:01:35.596 --> 00:01:39.491
the volume of the gas itself,
the molecules of the gas,

00:01:39.491 --> 00:01:43.131
is negligible relative to
the volume of the container.

00:01:43.131 --> 00:01:46.298
So, gas molecule volume is negligible.

00:01:58.545 --> 00:02:00.885
Now, it turns out there are no gases

00:02:00.885 --> 00:02:03.013
that are absolutely true ideal gases.

00:02:03.013 --> 00:02:05.797
Obviously, all gases,
their actual molecules,

00:02:05.797 --> 00:02:09.497
do take up some volume and there will be

00:02:09.497 --> 00:02:11.651
some type of intermolecular interactions

00:02:11.651 --> 00:02:15.138
in terms of even van der Waals
forces and whatever else.

00:02:15.138 --> 00:02:17.917
But it turns out, under most conditions

00:02:17.917 --> 00:02:20.166
that we're dealing with in a lot of gases,

00:02:20.166 --> 00:02:21.883
that these are reasonable assumptions.

00:02:21.883 --> 00:02:22.946
Or at least many conditions

00:02:22.946 --> 00:02:24.992
these are reasonable assumptions.

00:02:24.992 --> 00:02:28.959
In particular, these are reasonable....

00:02:28.959 --> 00:02:32.844
So, this is reasonable for real gases....

00:02:32.844 --> 00:02:35.927
Reasonable assumptions for real gases

00:02:44.749 --> 00:02:48.916
at relatively high
temperatures and low pressures.

00:02:52.090 --> 00:02:53.730
And, obviously, that's going to depend

00:02:53.730 --> 00:02:55.165
on which gas we're talking about how

00:02:55.165 --> 00:02:59.173
high of a temperature you
need or how low of a pressure.

00:02:59.173 --> 00:03:00.442
Or another way of thinking about it is

00:03:00.442 --> 00:03:04.085
these assumptions where gases
become less and less ideal

00:03:04.085 --> 00:03:07.071
as you approach their condensation point.

00:03:07.071 --> 00:03:07.904
So, if you start to really

00:03:07.904 --> 00:03:09.893
lower the temperature or
increase the pressure,

00:03:09.893 --> 00:03:13.159
you're more likely to go from
a gas form to liquid form.

00:03:13.159 --> 00:03:15.659
And, as you approach
that condensation point,

00:03:15.659 --> 00:03:20.156
your gas is going to behave
less and less like an ideal gas.

00:03:20.156 --> 00:03:22.936
But, as we've seen in many
videos, if your gas is...

00:03:22.936 --> 00:03:25.151
If you can make these assumptions,

00:03:25.151 --> 00:03:28.060
then it's reasonable to
apply the ideal gas law.

00:03:28.060 --> 00:03:31.048
That the pressure times the
volume of your ideal gas

00:03:31.048 --> 00:03:33.296
is going to be equal
to the number of moles

00:03:33.296 --> 00:03:36.695
times the universal gas constant

00:03:36.695 --> 00:03:39.933
times the temperature measured in Kelvin.

00:03:39.933 --> 00:03:43.865
Now, let's, first of all, think about why

00:03:43.865 --> 00:03:46.564
this is reasonable for most gases

00:03:46.564 --> 00:03:48.896
at relatively high
temperatures and low pressures.

00:03:48.896 --> 00:03:51.395
And then, we'll think about
where this breaks down

00:03:51.395 --> 00:03:53.195
as we can approach the condensation point

00:03:53.195 --> 00:03:54.751
where the temperature is lower

00:03:54.751 --> 00:03:57.372
or where the pressure is a lot higher.

